Bayesian Model Examples

5 Turnout: logit/probit models for binary data

library("tidyverse")
library("rstanarm")
library("rstan")

5.1 Data

The data comprise the first 2,000 (of 15,000+) observations in the 1992 American National Election Studies (ANES). These data are included in the Zelig package as turnout and analyzed in King, Tomz, and Wittenberg (2000).

data("turnout", package = "Zelig")
glimpse(turnout)
#> Observations: 2,000
#> Variables: 5
#> $ race    <fct> white, white, white, white, white, white, white, white...
#> $ age     <int> 60, 51, 24, 38, 25, 67, 40, 56, 32, 75, 46, 52, 22, 60...
#> $ educate <dbl> 14, 10, 12, 8, 12, 12, 12, 10, 12, 16, 15, 12, 12, 12,...
#> $ income  <dbl> 3.346, 1.856, 0.630, 3.418, 2.785, 2.387, 4.286, 9.320...
#> $ vote    <int> 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1, ...

We will model voting turnout as a function of covariates (age, education, income, race).

turnout_formula <- vote ~ poly(age, 2) + educate + income + race

5.2 Logit Model

Let \(y_i \in \{0, 1\}\) be the decision to vote by respondent \(i\) for \(i \in 1, \dots, n\), \[ \begin{aligned}[t] y_i &\sim \mathsf{Bernoulli}(\pi_i) , \\ \pi_i &= \frac{1}{1 + e^{-\eta_i}} , \\ \eta_i &= \alpha + x_i \beta, \end{aligned} \] where \(x_i\) is a vector of covariates. The regression parameters, \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\), are given weakly informative priors on the logit scale, \[ \begin{aligned}[t] \alpha &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(0, 16) , \\ \beta_k &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(0, 4) . \end{aligned} \]

The logit model in Stan is

turnout_mod_logit <- stan_model("stan/logit.stan")
  data {
  // response
  int N;
  int y[N];
  // covariates
  int K;
  matrix[N, K] X;
  // priors
  real alpha_loc;
  real alpha_scale;
  vector[K] beta_loc;
  vector[K] beta_scale;
}
parameters {
  real alpha;
  vector[K] beta;
}
transformed parameters {
  // linear predictor
  vector[N] eta;
  eta = alpha + X * beta;
}
model {
  alpha ~ normal(alpha_loc, alpha_scale);
  beta ~ normal(beta_loc, beta_scale);
  // y ~ bernoulli(inv_logit(eta));
  // this is faster and more numerically stable
  y ~ bernoulli_logit(eta);
}
generated quantities {
  // log-likelihood of each obs
  vector[N] log_lik;
  // probability
  vector[N] mu;
  for (i in 1:N) {
    mu[i] = inv_logit(eta[i]);
    log_lik[i] = bernoulli_logit_lpmf(y[i] | eta[i]);
  }
}

turnout_data <- within(list(), {
  N <- nrow(turnout)
  X <- scale(model.matrix(update(turnout_formula, . ~ 0 + .),
                                 data = turnout))
  K <- ncol(X)
  y <- turnout$vote
  alpha_loc <- 0
  alpha_scale <- 10
  beta_loc <- rep(0, K)
  beta_scale <- rep(2.5, K)
})
turnout_fit_logit <- sampling(turnout_mod_logit, data = turnout_data)
turnout_fit_logit

5.3 Probit Model

The only difference between the logit and probit models are in the link function. The probit model uses the normal distribution CDF function instead of the inverse logit. \[ \begin{aligned}[t] \pi_i &= \Phi(\eta_i) , \end{aligned} \] where \(\Phi\) is the standard normal distribution CDF. The priors for the probit model are adjusted by a facto of 1.6, corresponding to dnorm(0) / dlogis(0), \[ \begin{aligned}[t] \alpha &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(0, 16), \\ \beta_k &\sim \mathsf{Normal}(0, 4) . \end{aligned} \]

turnout_data <- within(turnout_data, {
  alpha_scale <- 16
  beta_scale <- rep(4, K)
})

The probit model in Stan is

turnout_mod_probit <- stan_model("stan/probit.stan")
  data {
  // response
  int N;
  int y[N];
  // covariates
  int K;
  matrix[N, K] X;
  // priors
  real alpha_mean;
  real alpha_scale;
  vector[K] beta_mean;
  vector[K] beta_scale;
}
parameters {
  real alpha;
  vector[K] beta;
}
transformed parameters {
  // linear predictor
  vector[N] eta;
  vector[N] mu;
  eta = alpha + X * beta;
  // mu = Phi(eta);
  // Phi_approx is faster
  mu = Phi_approx(eta);
}
model {
  alpha ~ normal(alpha_mean, alpha_scale);
  beta ~ normal(beta_mean, beta_scale);
  y ~ bernoulli(mu);
}
generated quantities {
  // log-likelihood of each obs
  vector[N] log_lik;
  for (i in 1:N) {
    log_lik[i] = bernoulli_lpmf(y[i] | mu[i]);
  }
}

Fit the model.

turnout_fit_probit <-
  sampling(turnout_mod_probit,
           data = turnout_data)
#> Warning in is.na(x): is.na() applied to non-(list or vector) of type 'NULL'
#> Warning in FUN(X[[i]], ...): data with name alpha_mean is not numeric and
#> not used
#> Warning in is.na(x): is.na() applied to non-(list or vector) of type 'NULL'
#> Warning in FUN(X[[i]], ...): data with name beta_mean is not numeric and
#> not used
#> failed to create the sampler; sampling not done
turnout_fit_probit
#> Stan model 'probit' does not contain samples.

5.4 rstanarm

These models can also be estimated with the rstanarm function stan_glm.

turnout_fit_logit2 <-
  stan_glm(turnout_formula,
           family = binomial(),
           data = turnout)
turnout_fit_logit2

For the probit model, the priors need to be reduced.

turnout_fit_probit2 <-
  stan_glm(turnout_formula,
           family = binomial(link = "probit"),
           prior_intercept = normal(location = 0, scale = 8, autoscale = TRUE),
         prior = normal(location = 0, scale = 1.5, autoscale = TRUE),
         init = 0, chains = 1,
         data = turnout)
turnout_fit_probit2

Questions

  1. Estimate the posterior distribution of the average marginal effect for each covariate using the methods in Hanmer and Kalkan (2012).
  2. Estimate the expected percent correctly predicted (ePCP) and percent correctly predicted (PCP) as discussed in the cosponsorship data.
  3. Estimate a generalized logit model to allow for asymmetric effects of covariates as described in the General Beetles example and Nagler (1994). Describe the substantive meaning of this generalization.
  4. Is there any difference in the fit of the probit and logit? Which observations fit better or worse.
  5. Estimate the model with a Student’s \(t\) CDF instead of logit or probit. This is called a robit model Liu (2005). Compare its fit and estimates to those of the logit. Which observations fit better or worse? Describe the substantive meaning of this generalization.
